node.text:
Translating past phantoms of personal experiences, Jo Ann Bitagcol and Nature Shankar revives the evanescence of rather-forgotten memories through textile-based works.

Through process-driven works, Nature journeys us through the intricate webs of her cultural experiences by reuse of what she terms ‘materials of comfort’ - repurposed textiles and fabrics bearing personal significance. Nature’s therapeutic process transforms timeless materials into interpretative expressions of her resilience against hardships. 

What would conventionally be termed as objects of evil, Jo Ann redefines ‘voodoo dolls’ as objects of blessing and mediums of her path to renewal. Her work reunites seemingly opposing forces, bringing them together to create an inevitable balance- demonstrating through fabric of the acceptance of a path to light with darkness in its wake.

Journey through the works of both artists in a unique virtual experience, beginning March 23rd till April 1st.

Learn more on https://artfairphilippines.com/gallery/art-agenda-s-e-a/

Youths In Balaclava (YIB) is a design collective and streetwear brand that started when its founders were still in high school. Their work is characterised by a self-taught DIY aesthetic, and underlying commentaries about growing up in a working-class environment in Singapore. In the exhibition, YIB presents a set of 10 masks, each representing a member of the collective; as well as a terrarium-like sculptural display. The display’s design nods to Singapore’s geography as an island within a larger archipelago. Housed within various islands are prototypes and archival materials which tell the story of the brand and its evolution.

‘Twisted Paradise’ is now on display at ‘We’re Young Once.’ Click on the link in our book to book a slot. 

📅 : 8 - 30 January 
🕙 : Tuesday to Sunday, 10.30am to 7.00pm
📍: 63 Spottiswoode Park Road, Singapore 088651

Admission is free. 

#wereyoungonce

Affandi’s beach scene captures the intense latent energy of nature at work and is a testament to the true expressionistic quality of his works. What he is depicting goes beyond the realm of what can be captured by a realist or naturalist artist.

The abstract quality of time and force of nature actuated in ‘At The Beach’ is what sets Affandi apart from other artists, and places him in an interesting counterpoint to other commonly acknowledged artists working in an abstract language.

Come and view this beautiful work at ‘Everything Light Touches’, a unique upcoming exhibition at @theartshouse 

📅 : 20 January - 6 February 2022
🕙 : 10.00am to 7.00pm daily
 (Last admission 6.30pm) 
📍 : 1 Old Parliament Lane

Admission is free.

WE’RE BACK! 🎉

As restrictions ease in Indonesia, we are delighted to announce that our Jakarta gallery will be opening its doors again!

We invite you to visit us and experience @valasara's artworks in person. Make sure to see his installation, 𝘊𝘢𝘳𝘰𝘶𝘴𝘦𝘭, which displays Balinese performers moving on a rotating plate. Reminding us of amusement parks, the work represents a cultural spectacle from the perspective of an outsider. 

📆 25 August - 25 September 2021
🕚 Tues - Fri: 11AM - 4.30PM, Sat: 11AM - 2PM
📍 Wisma Geha, lt. 4, Jl. Timor No. 25

Please register your visit in the link in bio. We seek your cooperation to adhere to social distancing measures during this time and hope to see you soon!

Watch this to see the ideas behind our virtual exhibition 𝘍𝘳𝘰𝘮 𝘋𝘶𝘴𝘬 𝘵𝘰 𝘋𝘢𝘸𝘯 at Art Fair Philippines 2021! (@artfairph) ✨

Although not acquainted with each other, the Indonesian artist Umi Dachlan and the Spanish-Filipino artist Fernando Zóbel were interested in how abstraction offered meaningful and novel ways of interpreting the world. Instead of focusing on their national and regional identities, the two were captured by the idea of universality. Both artists felt that their modes of abstraction could speak to a global population, without any reference to specific locations, events or figures. Their practices prompt the question: What is it that connects us all?

Virtual Fair Dates:
📅 06.05.2021 - 15.05.2021

How to access the online fair 💻:
1. 🔗 Click the link in our bio
2. 🖼️ View our selection of works
3. If you see an artwork you love 💙, tap the enquiry button or 📩 contact us at info@artagendasea.org

#ArtAgendaSEA is pleased to present our new thematic exhibition, 𝘊𝘳𝘪𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘪𝘰𝘯 ✨

The exhibition features a bi-weekly evolving collection of Southeast Asian modern and contemporary art illustrating the key criteria of quality, authenticity, provenance, condition and rarity that we look for in a collectable work of art. Works of Singapore second-generation artists Tan Choh Tee, Anthony Poon and Arthur Yap amongst others are featured in the first iteration. 

📅 06.04.2021 - 23.05.2021

The exhibition features the modern Indonesian artist, Umi Dachlan (1942 – 2009), who created paintings that were sensitive in their commentary of global issues. The horrors pertaining to human rights during incidents like the May 1998 riots of Indonesia were harrowing and shocking, moving Dachlan to express her concerns for the state of humanity. With her deep exploration of natural and urban textures, she viewed the material world as a reflection of mankind.

View her works in person at #ArtAgendaJKT.

Affandi’s beach scene captures the intense latent energy of nature at work, and is a testament to the true expressionistic quality of his works. What he is depicting goes beyond the realm of what can be captured by a realist or naturalist artist. 

The abstract quality of time and force of nature actuated in "At The Beach" is what sets Affandi apart from other artists, and places him in an interesting counterpoint to other commonly acknowledged artists working in an abstract language.

View this work and many others in our current exhibiton, #ToSEA at #ArtAgendaSEA.

node.text:
Translating past phantoms of personal experiences, Jo Ann Bitagcol and Nature Shankar revives the evanescence of rather-forgotten memories through textile-based works.

Through process-driven works, Nature journeys us through the intricate webs of her cultural experiences by reuse of what she terms ‘materials of comfort’ - repurposed textiles and fabrics bearing personal significance. Nature’s therapeutic process transforms timeless materials into interpretative expressions of her resilience against hardships. 

What would conventionally be termed as objects of evil, Jo Ann redefines ‘voodoo dolls’ as objects of blessing and mediums of her path to renewal. Her work reunites seemingly opposing forces, bringing them together to create an inevitable balance- demonstrating through fabric of the acceptance of a path to light with darkness in its wake.

Journey through the works of both artists in a unique virtual experience, beginning March 23rd till April 1st.

Learn more on https://artfairphilippines.com/gallery/art-agenda-s-e-a/

if you have not seen the show, this is one not to be missed. Join us tomorrow for an exhibition tour of We're Young Once conducted by curator Ian Tee. Focusing on the theme of youth, the show features over 20 works by an intergenerational lineup of 15 Singapore art practitioners, including Amanda Heng, Lim Yew Kuan, Anthony Poon, Shubigi Rao, Tang Da Wu, Jeremy Sharma, Tay Ining and Youths In Balaclava. Some of the participating artists will also be in attendance. 

Following the tour, we are proud to screen North-South Line, Struggle No. 1 – No Response, a performance by La Tristesse Opera led by Tang Da Wu. Much like Tang's works in We're Young Once, the performance is an exploratory pull into the seeming void within. Its title plays with the mandarin translation of "north-south line"  (南北线 nanbei xian), transforming the phrase into "north-south limit" (南北限 nanbei xian). The performance lays the history of artists working to break through illusory walls.

node.text:
Lacquer painting is a distinctively Vietnamese modern art medium and Pham Hau is one of its most distinguished practitioners. Natural lacquer or s’on ta has been used by the Vietnamese for traditional decorative craft for centuries. It became a modern art medium in the late 1920s to early 1930s with the founding of L’Ecole des Beaux de L’indochine, where young Vietnamese artists developed techniques and visual effects with silk and lacquer under the tutelage of French art instructors. While at the art college, Pham Hau gathered a strong foundation in Western art principles which he applied in an inventive manner to the nascent medium of lacquer painting.

‘Pagodas in a Tonkin Landscape’ is a classic and doubtlessly idealised representation of nature, landscape and the distinctive architecture of Vietnamese religious and cultural. The panorama landscape view, spread across six panels, with its resplendent colour palette of gold, amber, vermillion and ochre amongst others, bestow grandeur, history, timelessness, and nostalgia all at once.

Come and view this beautiful work on display at ‘Everything Light Touches’ at @theartshouse

node.text:
‘Useless Things’ is Tang Da Wu’s first important body of work which he made while studying at Birmingham College in 1971. Tang taps into his Chinese heritage with a reference to Laozi’s ‘Tao Te Ching’ Chapter 11 (<<老子道德经>> 第十一章), which meditates on the idea of emptiness or void.

He illustrates this concept by literally filling up the empty spaces in everyday items such as kitchen utensils, ladders and even the space where one sits in front of a desk, thus rendering them “useless” things. The discourse about the void becomes more layered when one thinks about it in relation to the lost-wax technique used to cast Tang’s bronze sculptures in 1971.

We are open!

‘Everything Light Touches: Panorama Paintings from Private Collections’ features over a dozen exceptional artworks from private collections in Singapore. Many of the paintings are on view to the public for the very first time and demonstrate the wealth of cultural treasures in private hands here in Singapore.  

The thematic focus on panorama paintings gives us the opportunity to bring together and appraise works from familiar figures in Asian art history through fresh lens. Situated in Singapore’s Civic District and bearing almost 200 years of history, The Arts House is an ideal venue to frame these pictorial narratives in a historical context, serving as a meeting point for different cultures to intersect.

Don't miss this rare showcase, see you at @theartshouse 

📅 : 20 January - 6 February

After months of hard work, ‘Everything Light Touches’ is finally here. Curated by Art Agenda, the exhibition is spread across three historical rooms on the second floor of The Arts House. 

It’s a reveal of how artists have utilized the expansive breadth of creative possibilities offered by the panoramic format. In the large modern paintings curated for the exhibition, the featured artists have captured the most consequential of subject matters — historic scenes and landscapes conveyed with great passion and sentiments — suggesting how panorama paintings have had an outsized importance in the history of art.

Open to the public tomorrow, we look forward to welcoming you at The Arts House. 

📅 : 20 January - 6 February 
🕙 : 10.00am to 7.00pm daily
 (Last admission 6.30pm) 
📍 : Old Parliament Lane

Admission is free

Youths In Balaclava (YIB) is a design collective and streetwear brand that started when its founders were still in high school. Their work is characterised by a self-taught DIY aesthetic, and underlying commentaries about growing up in a working-class environment in Singapore. In the exhibition, YIB presents a set of 10 masks, each representing a member of the collective; as well as a terrarium-like sculptural display. The display’s design nods to Singapore’s geography as an island within a larger archipelago. Housed within various islands are prototypes and archival materials which tell the story of the brand and its evolution.

‘Twisted Paradise’ is now on display at ‘We’re Young Once.’ Click on the link in our book to book a slot. 

📅 : 8 - 30 January 
🕙 : Tuesday to Sunday, 10.30am to 7.00pm
📍: 63 Spottiswoode Park Road, Singapore 088651

Admission is free.

Lining up with the theme of ‘We’re Young Once’, we are conducting a 1 hour introductory art experiential workshop titled, “Unmasking Self: An Art Experiential Workshop” facilitated by clinical psychologist, Dr Belinda Teo. During this hands-on workshop, participants will have a glimpse of the potential therapeutic benefits of art therapy. You will have an opportunity to reflect on different aspects of your identity (e.g., culture, gender) and explore visual arts as a medium to cultivate a deeper appreciation of oneself. This activity focuses on the process and not the final product, so all you need is an openness to experiment, all within the creative space of an art gallery.
 
Who is this session for? This session is a fun introduction for people who are interested to explore the use of art to relieve stress, develop deeper self-awareness, or embark on the first step towards self-discovery. Individuals with varying levels of art experience are welcome and you do not need to be an art aficionado to join us.

Spaces are limited so quickly reserve your spot by clicking on the link in our bio.

Curated by Art Agenda, ‘Everything Light Touches’ is an exhibition that showcases more then a dozen of superlative panoramic pictures on loan from private collections in Singapore, presenting a capsule history of modern Asian art. 

Ranging from Tsuguharu Foujita’s paradisiac ‘Visionary Landscape’, to the wild, almost abstract gesticulations of expressionist painter Affandi in ‘At The Beach’, it is evident the panorama awakens profound sentiments within oneself.

Ian Tee is an artist and the curator behind ‘We’re Young Once’. His practice is an exploration of youth, in relation to the themes of rebellion, vulnerability and identity. Conflating the history of painting with the energy of subcultures, he is interested in how aesthetic narratives can be reworked and recontextualized.
 
Ian is also a curator at Art Agenda and the Associate Editor of Art & Market, a multimedia platform that presents specialist content on Southeast Asian art. He is the author of the monograph ‘Fadjar Sidik: Expressive Design’ (2020) and is preparing a forthcoming monograph on another post-war Indonesian artist, Nashar. 

Ian's work ‘未成年’ belongs to the first suite of Target Paintings exhibited at his debut solo exhibition ‘SWEET DREAMS’ (2019).

Come and view his work at ‘We’re Young Once’ and register a spot by clicking on the link in our bio.
